const faqs = [
  {
    q: "Is a 4K gaming monitor worth it?",
    a: "It depends on your GPU. 4K at high refresh rates demands serious hardware — you'll want at least an RTX 4070 Ti or RX 7900 XT to hit 60+ fps in modern games at 4K. If you play competitive esports titles, 1440p at 240Hz is usually a better investment. But for single-player games and immersion, 4K is a visible upgrade, especially on 27-inch and larger displays."
  },
  {
    q: "What refresh rate do I actually need for gaming?",
    a: "For most gamers, 144Hz–165Hz is the sweet spot. The jump from 60Hz to 144Hz is dramatic and immediately noticeable. Going from 144Hz to 240Hz is subtler — mainly beneficial in competitive shooters. 360Hz is almost exclusively for professional esports. If you play a mix of games, 165Hz gives you the best balance of smoothness and GPU headroom."
  },
  {
    q: "IPS vs VA vs OLED — which panel type is best for gaming?",
    a: "Each has trade-offs. IPS offers the best color accuracy and viewing angles but mediocre contrast (1000:1). VA panels have much better contrast (3000:1+) and deeper blacks but can suffer from ghosting in fast motion. OLED is the best overall — infinite contrast, perfect blacks, and the fastest response times — but costs more and carries burn-in risk. For most budgets, IPS is the safest choice. If you can afford OLED, it's the clear winner."
  },
  {
    q: "Does response time really matter?",
    a: "Yes, but the numbers are often misleading. Manufacturer-quoted response times (GtG) are best-case scenarios. What matters is real-world pixel transitions — a monitor with a 1ms GtG IPS panel will look noticeably sharper in motion than a 4ms VA panel. OLED panels at 0.03ms are in a league of their own. For competitive gaming, aim for 1ms GtG or better."
  },
