    q: "Do I need G-Sync or FreeSync?",
    a: "You need adaptive sync technology — either one. G-Sync is for Nvidia GPUs, FreeSync is for AMD. Most modern monitors support both ('G-Sync Compatible' works with Nvidia cards on FreeSync monitors). Adaptive sync eliminates screen tearing without the input lag of V-Sync. It's essentially a must-have feature in 2026, and virtually all gaming monitors above $150 include it."
  },
  {
    q: "Is a curved monitor better for gaming?",
    a: "Curved monitors are better for immersion, especially at ultrawide (34\"+) sizes where flat panels cause noticeable distortion at the edges. For 27-inch monitors, the difference is subtle — a 1000R or 1500R curve adds a slight sense of depth but isn't transformative. Curved VA panels are very common because VA technology bends more easily than IPS. For competitive FPS, flat is generally preferred; for RPGs and racing games, curved enhances the experience."
  },
