            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      ))}

      <h2>How We Chose These Monitors</h2>
      <p>Every gaming monitor on this list was evaluated on six core criteria:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Image Quality:</strong> Color accuracy, contrast ratio, black levels, and HDR performance. We measured with a colorimeter and tested in both bright and dark room conditions.</li>
        <li><strong>Motion Clarity:</strong> Real-world response times, overshoot, and how clean fast-moving objects appear. We used UFO tests and fast-paced shooters to evaluate ghosting and smearing.</li>
        <li><strong>Input Lag:</strong> End-to-end latency from GPU output to pixels changing on screen. Critical for competitive gaming where every millisecond matters.</li>
        <li><strong>Build Quality:</strong> Stand adjustability, panel coating, port selection, and OSD usability. A great panel in a terrible housing is still a frustrating experience.</li>
        <li><strong>Value:</strong> Performance relative to price. A $200 monitor competing with $350 alternatives scores higher than a $1,100 flagship that's marginally better than $800 options.</li>
        <li><strong>Versatility:</strong> How well the monitor handles different use cases — competitive gaming, single-player immersion, creative work, and console compatibility.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Gaming Monitor Buying Guide</h2>

      <h3>Resolution: 1080p vs 1440p vs 4K</h3>
      <p>1440p is the current sweet spot for gaming. It's a massive visual upgrade over 1080p without the GPU demands of 4K. At 27 inches, 1440p delivers a pixel density of 109 PPI — sharp enough that individual pixels are invisible at normal viewing distance. 4K (163 PPI at 27") looks noticeably crisper but requires roughly twice the GPU power. Stick with 1440p unless you have an RTX 4070 Ti or better and primarily play single-player games.</p>

      <h3>Refresh Rate: How High Do You Need?</h3>
      <p>The jump from 60Hz to 144Hz is transformative — everything from cursor movement to in-game camera panning feels dramatically smoother. Going from 144Hz to 240Hz is a subtler improvement that's most noticeable in fast-paced shooters. 360Hz is diminishing returns territory and only matters for professional-level competitive play. For most gamers, 165Hz is the sweet spot: noticeable improvement over 144Hz, widely available, and doesn't require a top-tier GPU.</p>

      <h3>Panel Types: IPS vs VA vs OLED</h3>
      <p><strong>IPS (In-Plane Switching)</strong> is the most popular gaming panel type. Excellent color accuracy, wide viewing angles, and fast response times. The downside is mediocre contrast (typically 1000:1) — blacks look grayish in dark rooms.</p>
      <p><strong>VA (Vertical Alignment)</strong> panels offer 3x better contrast than IPS (3000:1+), delivering much deeper blacks. The trade-off is slower pixel transitions, which cause noticeable ghosting in fast motion — especially in dark-to-light scenes. Best for atmospheric games and movies if you're not playing twitchy shooters.</p>
      <p><strong>OLED</strong> is the best technology overall: infinite contrast, perfect blacks, and the fastest response times (0.03ms). The drawbacks are higher cost and burn-in risk from static UI elements. If your budget allows it and you manage screen saver settings, OLED is the clear winner for gaming.</p>

      <h3>Response Time: What the Numbers Actually Mean</h3>
      <p>Manufacturers quote GtG (gray-to-gray) response times, but these are best-case numbers and not standardized. A "1ms" IPS panel and a "1ms" VA panel will look very different in motion. What actually matters is the full range of pixel transitions and overshoot. OLED panels genuinely hit 0.03ms across all transitions. IPS panels are next best (1-4ms real-world). VA panels are slowest (4-8ms real-world with notable dark smearing).</p>

      <h3>Adaptive Sync: G-Sync vs FreeSync</h3>
      <p>Adaptive sync eliminates screen tearing by matching the monitor's refresh rate to your GPU's frame output. G-Sync is Nvidia's version, FreeSync is AMD's. In 2026, the distinction barely matters — most monitors are "G-Sync Compatible" and work with both Nvidia and AMD GPUs. The only monitors with dedicated G-Sync modules (which add a premium) are high-end models, and the real-world difference over G-Sync Compatible is minimal for most users.</p>

